16K Price Crash:
In August 1979, a single 16Kx1 chip (4116) cost about $11.24 retail.
By January 1980, prices from mail-order suppliers like Jameco dropped to $9.95.
Japanese firms began selling DRAM at or below US market rates to capture share.
Costs fell roughly 30-35% annually as production volume doubled.

By 1980, 4K chips were "legacy" parts. They required the same amount of
manufacturing effort, so their price-per-bit was significantly higher.

Same or lower manufacturing cost for 16Kx8 (16KB) vs 4Kx8x2 (8KB).


64K Price Crash:
In early 1981, 64K chips were "premium" components, costing roughly $50.00 each.
By late 1982, the price plummeted to approximately $5.00–$6.00 at the wholesale
level due to massive production scaling by Japanese manufacturers. 

Mid-1983 was the tipping point: 64K cheaper than 48K.


