What if I started with 256 x 192 ?

• 1 MHz 6502            (bus sharing on low cycle)
• 16K RAM @ 450ns cycle (best price-per-bit in 1980)
• 2K character ROM      (256 glyphs) (merge with BASIC ROMs?)
• 8K BASIC ROM          (maybe 2 x 4K)
• 32 x 24 text mode
• 256 x 192 graphics
• 16 colors
• palette per cell (1 of 4 palettes; 2 bits per cell) [32*24/2 = 384 nibble Color-RAM; 512x4 SRAM]
• 4 palettes [4*4 = 16 bytes in VDP]
• 128/256 custom characters [uses 1KB/2KB] (switchable)
• 32-byte line buffer [share the 512x4 SRAM @ 250ns cycle]
• steal 6 CPU cycles in the right border (see timing below)

Every 8 pixels can perform 2 DRAM accesses @ 500ns:
The CPU gets 1 access per tile (read/write)
The VDP gets 1 access per tile (RAM/ROM glyph read)
The VDP gets 3 accesses to Color-RAM per tile (char low, char high, attribute) @ 250ns
The CPU gets 1 access to Color-RAM per tile (the last 250ns slot)

We can enable half-palette mode: top bit of each character selects the low/high half of
the palette: 8 x 2-color palettes per line.

We can switch to lo-res mode and use 4 colors per tile at half-res.

We can change palettes on each line, or even during the line.

We can switch to 16-color mode that stores 256 x 16-color nibbles in Color-RAM,
a single color per character over 8 lines. Software must upload new colors every line,
at a rate of 32 nibbles per line. Color 1. Palette 0 is used for remaining colors.

We can enable an interrupt on every 8th line at the end of the character row,
to enable this 16-color upload.

We can emulate 40-column mode using 6-column characters in APA 256 x 192 mode.
We can switch to 6-column color mode, reading colors from Color-RAM every 6 columns,
which means 320 x 16-color nibbles over 8 lines; upload 40 nibbles per line.
Palettes also fit: 40*24/2 = 480 palettes in 512 nibbles.
We have extra SRAM space and bandwidth since there's no line buffering in APA modes.

We can support 64-column 16-color mode: read colors every 4 columns;
448/64 = 8 lines; upload 64 nibbles/line.
Palettes won't fit: 64*24/2 = 768 palettes in 512 nibbles.


