Clock Skew Budget: In 1980, a safe design rule was to assume a 10–20% timing margin to account for
the gate array's internal interconnect resistance.

Fan-out Sensitivity: 74LS has a typical fan-out of 20, but internal gate array cells often had much
weaker drive strengths. If your minterm logic has high-fan-out nodes, you must prototype them with
buffers (74LS244) to simulate the "loading" the gate array will face.

Setup/Hold Times: For flip-flops (e.g., 74LS74), the typical setup time (ts) is 20 ns.
When designing for a 1980 release, targeting a 10 MHz to 25 MHz system clock is the "safe"
envelope for volume-produced gate arrays.

