An AOI22 (74LS51) was often a single "macro" that counted as maybe 4–6 gates but only cost one propagation delay.
Jellybean parts: 74LS00 (NAND), 74LS02 (NOR), 74LS04 (Inv), 74LS08 (AND), 74LS32 (OR).

The NAND-NAND Trick: any Sum-of-Products (minterm) logic can be built entirely out of 74LS00s or 74LS10s
(Triple 3-input NAND). This was the gold standard for 1980 designs because NAND gates were the cheapest
and fastest TTL components.

When you lay out the 74LS version for enthusiasts, try to group your Address Decoders (74LS138/139) close to the CPU and the Data Transceivers (74LS245) close to the DRAM. This mimics the physical layout constraints of 1980 motherboards where long traces added "hidden" propagation delays (approx 1.5ns to 2ns per foot of PCB trace).

The 6502 is an NMOS chip with high input capacitance. If your 74LS161 output is too "lazy" (slow rise time),
the 6502 can glitch. In 1980, designers often used a 74LS04 with a pull-up resistor to "sharpen" the clock edges.

Divide-by-14 counter: use bit 'D' as the 6502 clock.
Align the counter values so bit D has 7/7 duty cycle (load 1, reload on 14)

If your Φ2 is 489ns, and your 74LS address decoders take ~40ns to settle, the DRAM has ~449ns to get data to the CPU.
Even the slowest 4116-25 (250ns) DRAMs will work perfectly here. You have nearly 200ns of "safety margin,"
which is very generous for 1980. (I need a 100ns setup time. 6502 latches the data on falling Φ2.)
489 - 40 - 250 - 100 = 99ns margin. Tads = 225ns after falling Φ1; very stable by rise of Φ2, RAS immediately.

14.318 MHz clock, each "tick" is ~70 ns (for DRAM timing, max gate delays, etc)

